Subject: Re: Semi Re: Fractal Encryption

At 11:52 PM 1/18/99 +0200, you wrote:
>Hello Thomas.
>
>On 18-Jan-99, Thomas Cobb wrote:
>
>>>> In which case XOR
>>>> encryption is exactly as effective, but less CPU intensive.
>
>> Can someone explain to me what is wrong with xor encryption.  Surely
>> if the key is long enough (say the length of the thing you are going
>> to encrypt) then it is going to be pretty hard to crack.
>
>Actually it's impossible to crack, without at least a partial key, and I
think XOR encryption rules :o)
>
>

It's only impossible if the key is as long as the "text" and the key is
100% random...


Text XOR Key = Encrypted

Encrypted XOR Key = Text

It's posible to "take away" the key then you just have the Text XOR'ed and
then you can use statistics and you have the Decrypted text.
It's harder if the text/key is small.



I'll post the solution to this within a few days...

Kai



